When choosing "Warning" in unnecessary cast or instanceof, it would be great to make a difference between exact match and compatible cast. Examples:

// completely useless, should be reported as a warning
int w = (int)component.getWidth();
long lw = (long)component.getWidth();

// cast used as a check
public List nodes() {
	Iterator it = graph.getNodeIterator();
	ArrayList nodes = new ArrayList();

        while (it.hasNext())
                // must have good type
        	nodes.add((MyNode)it.next());

	return nodes;
}

Hope you like the idea.

Interestingly, we used to report this using a different message, and we got requests to unify both warnings... <g>

Complete testcase:
import java.util.*;
public class X {
	public void nodes() {
	        Iterator it = null;
	        ArrayList nodes = new ArrayList();

	        while (it.hasNext())
	                // must have good type
	                nodes.add((X)it.next());
	}
}

Feels to me that if the explicit cast is mandated, it could be made more obvious:
import java.util.*;
public class X {
        public void nodes() {
                Iterator it = null;
                ArrayList nodes = new ArrayList();

                while (it.hasNext()) {
                        // must have good type
                        X x = (X) it.next();
                        nodes.add(x);
                }
        }
}

I believe that this warning is useful, for detecting cases where you set unnecessary constraints to your objects. If you really mean the constraint, then what I suggested will make it explicit.

Note that when using generics it will also become more obvious due to parameterization being visually present in the code.

My inclination would be to not change the current story, and rather have user code explicitly indicate what it wants. Introducing yet another option is going to miss all cases at once, where quite a few where quite interesting actually.

