Given a set of three projects that generate an xlint:cantFindType error, the default order in which the projects are built, as dictated by alphabetical ordering on project name, will change whether the error is reported on a clean build, or only when a syntactical change is made to the Aspect class.

To reproduce (to save time, see test attachments for bug 159704, which creates these three projects):

- create a Java project called "ThirdPartyLibrary"
- add a single Java class, called "ThirdPartyLibrary", with a public void method "thirdPartyOperation()". 

- create an AspectJ project called "UserLibrary"
- add a single Java class, called "UserLibraryClass", with a method "doStuff" which simply instantiates ThirdPartyLibrary and invokes "thirdPartyOperation()", thus:

   public void doStuff() {
      new ThirdPartyLibrary().thirdPartyOperation();
   }

- create another AspectJ project, called "UserAspects"
- add an Aspect called "UserAspect" with the following advice:

   before() : call(UserLibraryClass.new(..)) {  
      System.out.println("UserLibraryClass constructor()");
   } 

A clean build of your workspace should result in no errors. Now add a '+' to the adivce in UserAspect, thus:

   before() : call(UserLibraryClass+.new(..)) {  

and save the source file. One error should appear on the project "UserLibrary", of type "Xlint:cantFindType".  Now run a clean build of your workspace again.  The error has magically disappeared.  Remove the '+' introduced previously.  Save the source file again, and the error re-appears.  Run another clean build of the workspace, and the error disappears again.

Now refactor the name of the UserAspects project to "UserLibraryAspects".  Make the same behavioural tests as before, making syntactical changes to the aspect file and running clean builds.  The error reporting is now consistent.

